3. Mandatory KBeam Compatibility

You may modify, extend, rebrand, configure, or integrate the Software, but
every copy, fork, hosted deployment, modified version, derivative work,
redistributed copy, hosted source release, and substantial continuation that
includes or is based on the KBeam-Compatible Login flow must preserve a working
KBeam-Compatible Login path and satisfy the Minimum Compatibility Requirements.

You must not remove, rename, disable, obscure, break, or make non-functional
the KBeam-Compatible Login flow, the Protected Compatibility Identifiers, or
the technical compatibility requirements described in the KBeam Compatibility
Specification.

You may add other login methods, wallet providers, access policies, user
systems, payment flows, application-specific authorization layers, routes,
storage systems, deployment topologies, or user interfaces, provided that the
KBeam-Compatible Login flow remains available and interoperable with the KBeam
wallet application.

If You change implementation details, APIs, routes, deployment topology,
storage, frontend UI, or session handling, You are responsible for ensuring
that KBeam users can still unlock the integrated protected area through the
KBeam-Compatible Login flow.

You must test and maintain the KBeam-Compatible Login flow. Before You publicly
deploy, redistribute, or make available a modified version, fork, derivative
work, hosted service, or substantial continuation that includes or is based on
the KBeam-Compatible Login flow, You must run compatibility tests or equivalent
verification procedures sufficient to confirm that the KBeam-Compatible Login
flow still works. You must repeat this verification after material changes that
could affect login tickets, KBeam app links, challenge generation, signature
approval, waiting-browser status updates, session handoff, or protected-area
unlock behavior.

If You discover that the KBeam-Compatible Login flow is broken in Your public
deployment, redistributed version, fork, derivative work, hosted source
release, or substantial continuation, You must make commercially reasonable
efforts to repair it, disable the broken public release until repaired, or
clearly withdraw the affected KBeam-compatible login claim. You may not
knowingly distribute or operate a version that claims KBeam compatibility while
the KBeam-Compatible Login flow is non-functional.

